description: Exploit and remediate a OS Command Injection exposure. The application allows users to read files they previously stored. In order to read a file, the application executes an OS command, part of the OS command is built using unvalidated user input. This could allow attackers to execute dangerous commands directly on the operating system with the same privileges as the running vulnerable application.
topics: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an OS Command
title: OS Command Injection
trophyDescription: The candidate can remediate OS Command Injection exposures in Java.

infoList.title: Starting the exercise
infoList.description: When starting the exercise you will be presented with an Ubuntu desktop. Wait for Eclipse IDE and Firefox to launch.

infoList.title: Eclipse
infoList.description: Switch to Eclipse, click on the "Servers" tab, then click on "Start the Server" to launch the application server.

infoList.title: Firefox
infoList.description: Switch to Firefox, browse to: http://www.vulnerableapp.com:8050 . Login to the Vulnerable Application using the following credentials: user / password

infoList.title: Finishing the exercise
infoList.description: When you have completed the exercise, browse to Running Exercises" and click on "Mark Completed". Provisional results will be available in the "History" tab.

infoList.title: Troubleshooting
infoList.description: Restore source code: if you accidentally break the app's functionality, you can reset the app to the original source code using the shell script at: /home/rtf/Desktop/RTF/restoreSource.sh

flagList.instructions: Browse to "MyDocuments" tab. This screen allows for to view and upload files into the user's folder. Exploit the Command Execution exposure in the file input field, to return the hostname of the underlying OS.
Remediate the exposure by editing the actions.GetDocumentsAction.java class by using a Java API to read a file. Also ensure users can only read their own files.

hint.text: Change the String readFile(String path) to use the Java File API to read the contents of the file. Ensure appropriate authorization controls are in place with the chosen solution.
